http://www.thehindu.com/business/IOC-lines-up-Rs-1.8-lakh-crore-for-expansion/article14373687.ece

Mumbai: State-owned largest oil retailer and marketer Indian Oil Corporation (IOC) has lined up a massive capital expenditure plan of Rs 1.8 lakh crore to expand its refineries, set up marketing infrastrure, petrochemicals plants, LNG terminals and oil exploration business. Confirming the development B Ashok, chairman, IOC told The Hindu, “Of the Rs 1.8 lakh crore, Rs 50,000 crore each will set spent on refinery and marketing infrastructure and the rest will be used for natural gas, petrochemicals and other expansions.”The company is targeting to increase add another 24 million tonnes per annum (mtpa) of refinery capacity to exceed capacity of 100 mtpa by 2020. The company has already become India’s second largest petrochemicals producer after Reliance Industries with market share of 25 per cent. The company will be spending Rs 15,000 crore this year as part of its 56,200 crore targeted capex for the 12th five year plan and another Rs 72,000 crore in the next three years. The capex of Rs 1.8 lakh crore excludes the mega Maharashtra refinery project with capacity of 60 mtpa and investment of Rs 1.72 lakh crore. IOC is the lead partner for this refinery with 50 per cent stake, while the rest 50 per cent divided equally among HPCL and BPCL. 